  "duration": 119.68,
  "text": " The job you are doing now, and that you're certainly you were doing a year ago, is already gone. Like, it is never going to come back. What we're really focused on this year is turning everybody at Ramp into a builder. Notion Custom Agents allow us to give the team that lens into how they can think about not just doing work with AI, but actually creating AI tools that are off doing work for them. We've started to see this proliferation of agents. So you've got Q&A agents that are living in dozens of Slack channels, document producing agents like Enablement Eddie, which does sales enablement tasks, agents that are doing operational workflows. We've got one called Referral Bonus Roy. We get thousands of pieces of sales feedback every quarter from customers. It was getting painstakingly rolled up into reports for the business. The reality is that most of it didn't get used. We worked quickly with our data team and just started to pipe all of that sales feedback into Notion. And that to me was the light bulb moment to map something, to triage it to the right part of the roadmap had been this actually high judgment effort. Now, the product organization is more likely to be building the right things. The operations team that was having to do this manually is now spending more time thinking about what it all means. And then we can also see that hundreds of times account managers have been able to go back and kind of please and delight customers. I think it's really important to think about productivity not just as a combination of speed and efficiency, but also quality and output. And with things like custom agents, it gives you the ability to notice a workflow that you wish you could either add more power to or automate altogether. And it's hard to put a dollar value on that, but I'm pretty sure it's quite positive. Go in with a vague idea and ask Notion AI, how would you build a custom agent that can do X, Y, Z? ask me some questions, work with me let's build this thing together",
